, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Europe":"Europe","Pollington, Yorkshire, England":"Pollington, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pollington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name, evidently from Pollington (Yorkshire). The placename derives from an unknown first element + the Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The surname is now mainly found in Sussex, to which it appears to have migrated at an early date from Yorkshire."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":24,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Pollington was born about 1235, in Pollington, Yorkshire, England as the son of Thomas Pollington and Mrs Thomas Pollington. He married Joyce Cave in 1263, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1285, in his hometown, at the age of 51."},"et":{"about 1235–1285":"umbes 1235–1285","1235–1285":"1235–1285","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1260–1297":"1260–1297","1215–Male":"1215–Su